# 🎭 Real-Time AI Video Call with Face Swap
## WebRTC + Deep-Live-Cam Integration

---

## 📁 File Structure

```
webrtc-test/
├── client/                     ← React frontend
│   └── src/
│       ├── VideoCall.js        ← ✅ UPDATED — now includes face swap
│       └── Room.js             ← ✅ unchanged
├── serve.js                    ← ✅ Node.js signaling server (port 3001)
├── server.py                   ← ✅ NEW — Python AI face-swap server (port 8000)
├── models/
│   └── inswapper_128.onnx      ← ⬇️ Download separately (see below)
└── README.md
```

---

## 🚀 How to Run (3 Steps)

### Step 1 — Start the Node.js Signaling Server
```bash
cd webrtc-test
node serve.js
# Runs on http://localhost:3001
```

### Step 2 — Start the Python AI Server
```bash
# First time only — install dependencies:
pip install fastapi uvicorn websockets opencv-python numpy pillow python-multipart insightface onnxruntime

# Then run:
python server.py
# Runs on http://localhost:8000
```

### Step 3 — Start the React Frontend
```bash
cd webrtc-test/client
npm install
npm start
# Runs on http://localhost:3000
```

---

## ⬇️ Download the Face Swap Model

Create a `models/` folder and download the model:

```bash
mkdir models
# Download inswapper_128.onnx (~500MB) from:
# https://github.com/facefusion/facefusion-assets/releases/download/models/inswapper_128.onnx

# Place it at:
# webrtc-test/models/inswapper_128.onnx
```

> **Note:** Without the model, the server runs in **passthrough mode** — video still works, just no face swap.

---

## 🎯 How to Use Face Swap in a Call

1. **Start a room** — Click "Create New Room" in the UI
2. **Open a second tab** — Paste the Room ID and join
3. **Upload your source face** — Click "Upload Source Face" and pick a photo
4. **Start face swap** — Click "▶ Start Face Swap"
5. The other person in the call will now see your face replaced!

---

## 🏗️ Architecture

```
User Camera/Mic
      │
      ▼
[React Frontend]  ──frames──►  [Python AI Server :8000]
      │                              │ InsightFace
      │            ◄──processed──────┘
      │
      ▼ (processed stream)
[Socket.io Signaling :3001]
      │
      ▼
[WebRTC Peer Connection]
      │
      ▼
Remote User sees swapped face
```

---

## 🔧 Environment Variables (optional)

Create `client/.env`:
```
REACT_APP_AI_SERVER_URL=ws://localhost:8000
REACT_APP_AI_HTTP_URL=http://localhost:8000
```

For remote deployment (e.g. ngrok):
```
REACT_APP_AI_SERVER_URL=wss://your-ai-server.ngrok.io
REACT_APP_AI_HTTP_URL=https://your-ai-server.ngrok.io
```

---

## ⚡ Performance Tips

| Setting | Value | Notes |
|--------|-------|-------|
| Frame rate | 20fps | Set `FRAME_INTERVAL_MS = 50` in VideoCall.js |
| Resolution | 480x270 | Lower = faster AI processing |
| GPU | NVIDIA recommended | InsightFace uses CUDA if available |
| Latency target | < 200ms | Achievable on local network |

---

## 🐛 Troubleshooting

| Problem | Fix |
|---------|-----|
| "AI Offline" in UI | Make sure `python server.py` is running |
| No face swap effect | Upload a source face image first |
| Model not found | Download `inswapper_128.onnx` to `models/` |
| Camera not working | Allow camera permissions in browser |
| CUDA error | Install `onnxruntime-gpu` instead of `onnxruntime` |
| Peers can't connect | Check firewall allows port 3001 |

---

## 📦 Full Dependency List

**Node.js (serve.js):**
```bash
npm install express socket.io uuid
```

**Python (server.py):**
```bash
pip install fastapi uvicorn websockets opencv-python numpy pillow python-multipart insightface onnxruntime
```

**React (client/):**
```bash
npm install socket.io-client simple-peer
```